body: Thank you @nicois, do you know exactly what keys existed among the three mentioned in the command execution when you ran it? Thanks.

I don't fully understand the RDB binary structure, but I'm 90% sure it only had the notes_1 stream defined.


$ grep schedule_1 /var/redis/6400/dump.rdb.crashing 
$ grep notes_1 /var/redis/6400/dump.rdb.crashing 
Binary file /var/redis/6400/dump.rdb.crashing matches
$ grep patient_1 /var/redis/6400/dump.rdb.crashing

I don't know if it helps, but I have kept a copy of the RDB, and when I tried restarted redis it would crash immediately, so I can reproduce the fault. Unfortuanately the content of the notes is sensitive, so I cannot share the file with you - though if there are any operations you'd like me to perform on it, I would be very happy to do so.

Not sure if it's helpful, but when I reload the failing RDB, this is what happens when I try to operate on the notes_1 stream. Note that I have to restart the server after the XREAD and XRANGE, as the server crashes.
Also, I don't think it's relevant, but I do have a password on the server, which I have stripped from the lines below.

$ redis-cli-streams -p 6400  XREAD STREAMS notes_1 0 | wc
Error: Server closed the connection
      0       0       0
$ redis-cli-streams -p 6400 XRANGE notes_1 - + | wc                                                                                                               
Error: Server closed the connection
      0       0       0
$ redis-cli-streams -p 6400 XADD new_stream_1 '*' foo bar                                                                                                         
1510174431610-0
That's super helpful @nicois ! Please could you send me the RDB file in some way? My email address is antirez - at - gmail
Thanks! Appreciated. Leaving tomorrow for a conference but I'll try to check it on the go.
Might be related to https://github.com/antirez/redis/issues/4349 (reading >4096 bytes from a stream)?
It's absolutely possible. These notes include json-encoded RTF documents, some of which could certainly be 4kb or larger.
Back from my travel, thanks @nicois, @forkfork, yes it looks like it's the same. Investigating and reporting.

Ok there is a problem in listpack.c with strings with the 32 bit length encoding. Unfortunately even fixing the bug the fuzz tester is still reporting failures, so I've to investigate better what is happening. The listpack fuzz tester was yet not finished and it was not able to stress certain encoding types. I'll fix upstream in antirez/listpack directly and back port the fix here. Please note: **the data structure itself generated by XADD** is broken, so fixing this bug will not fix the data, that will have to be re-created from scratch. I can already say this because of the bug I already found, regardless of the next one (fund by the fuzzer) that is still pending.
